<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_ui_action` row that
    declares the `Start Progress` form button on the `x_casemgmt_case` custom
    table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    The concrete scope identifier `x_casemgmt` is used consistently throughout
    this repository per ../docs/state-machine.md: "ServiceNow Update Set imports
    use a standard XML parser, so the scope id must be concrete in every record
    before the Update Set is exported." All sibling XML records in this Update
    Set use `x_casemgmt` byte-for-byte; this UI Action follows the same
    convention. The AAP Section 0.7.2 placeholder `x_[scope]_` is a TEMPLATE
    that resolves to `x_casemgmt_` at materialization time.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim, row 2):
        From          To             Required condition / behavior
        Open          In Progress    assigned_agent populated AND member
                                     of assigned_group
                                     Failure: Surface form-level error

    This UI Action is the user-facing ENTRY POINT for the Open -> In Progress
    transition - the SECOND forward transition in the case state-machine
    (after Draft -> Open via case_open.xml, order=100). It surfaces a
    "Start Progress" button on the case form whenever the case is currently
    in `Open` status AND the current user is authorized (case_manager OR
    assigned case_agent). Clicking the button advances the case to In
    Progress status, provided that the transition guard
    `canTransitionToInProgress` from the central Script Include
    ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml passes
    (i.e., assigned_agent is populated AND a member of assigned_group).
    Failure surfaces a blocking gs.addErrorMessage on the form.

    THE STRICTER GUARD - WHY START PROGRESS IS DIFFERENT FROM OPEN:

        The sibling case_open.xml UI Action (Draft -> Open) requires only
        that `assigned_group` be populated. This Start Progress UI Action
        adds two MORE preconditions on top of that:

          1) `assigned_agent` must be populated (a specific person, not
             just a group, must own the case before work begins).
          2) `assigned_agent` must be a member of `assigned_group` (the
             agent and group must be consistent - the platform does not
             enforce this consistency at the column level via reference
             qualifier alone, so the Script Include encodes it as a
             runtime check via GlideRecord on sys_user_grmember).

        Both checks are encapsulated in the single Script Include method
        canTransitionToInProgress. The UI Action does NOT inline either
        check - per AAP Section 0.7.2 Rule 5 ("Delegate to Script Include
        - DO NOT inline current.assigned_agent / membership validation"),
        the Script Include is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH and the same
        helper is shared with:
          - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml (the
            Flow Designer subflow that fires on the OnUpdate trigger of
            the two parent state-machine flows)
          - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml
            (the before-update BR that runs on EVERY case update including
            those triggered by direct Table API or scripted REST calls -
            so even a path that bypasses this UI Action gets the same
            membership check)

        Centralizing the guard in the Script Include guarantees that the
        error message text is identical across all callers (no drift
        between this UI Action's error and the flow's error), and future
        rule changes only need to be made in one place.

    SERVER-SIDE-ONLY PATTERN (matches sibling case_open.xml and case_resume.xml;
    contrasts with case_set_pending.xml):

        Unlike the Set Pending UI Action which uses a hybrid client+server
        pattern (it must collect the `pending_reason` value via prompt() on
        the client before submitting), this Start Progress UI Action runs
        ENTIRELY on the server. There is no input to collect - the
        transition has no required parameters beyond the assigned_agent
        and assigned_group fields that the operator should have populated
        on the form before clicking. The single click invokes the server
        script directly via the platform's standard form-button verb
        pipeline, with no <onclick> JavaScript and no client-side function
        definition.

        Phase 1 - User clicks the "Start Progress" button.
        Phase 2 - The platform evaluates the visibility <condition> on the
                  server when the form was rendered; the button is shown
                  only if the condition was true (status==Open AND user
                  is case_manager OR assigned case_agent).
        Phase 3 - The platform invokes the form-submit verb derived from
                  this UI Action's sys_name (`sysverb_x_casemgmt_case_
                  start_progress`).
        Phase 4 - The platform binds `current` (the case GlideRecord),
                  `gs` (GlideSystem), `action` (UI Action helper), and
                  evaluates the <script> body in a server sandbox.
        Phase 5 - The script performs four layers of defense-in-depth
                  validation (role, status, "Assigned only" for agents,
                  transition guard) before executing the transition.
        Phase 6 - The script sets current.status = 'In Progress' and calls
                  current.update() ONCE to persist the change.
        Phase 7 - The script calls action.setRedirectURL(current) to
                  refresh the form so the operator sees the updated status.

        The single current.update() call triggers the platform's full
        before-update Business Rule pipeline, including:
          - x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml (skipped because previous
            status was Open, not Closed)
          - x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml (skipped because
            current status is In Progress, not Draft)
          - x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml (re-validates
            assigned_agent membership; passes because the same membership
            check just ran in this UI Action's Script Include delegation;
            belt-and-suspenders defense in depth)
          - x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml (the
            companion BR that ALSO clears pending_reason on transitions
            INTO In Progress; for the Open -> In Progress edge there is
            typically no pending_reason set anyway, but the BR is a no-op
            in that case)
          - x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml (skipped because current status
            is In Progress, not Closed)

        The two Flow Designer flows (general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        complaint_state_machine.xml) also fire on this update via their
        OnUpdate triggers filtered on `status` change, calling the
        validate_inprogress_transition subflow which itself delegates to
        x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToInProgress() -
        the SAME helper this UI Action calls. Together they form a
        defense-in-depth guard pair: the UI Action blocks the transition
        at the form level (better UX), and the flow blocks it at the
        workflow level (catches Table API and other non-form paths).

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only context, NOT byte-for-byte
    ported per AAP Section 0.2.1):

        acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
        line 79-114 - the central ArkCase case state-machine service. Its
        `changeCaseState(auth, caseId, newState, ipAddress)` method:

            1) Loads the CaseFile by ID (line 85)
            2) Returns early if status unchanged (lines 88-91) - mirrored
               here by the defense-in-depth check `current.status != 'Open'`
               (we do NOT redundantly re-check whether the new state equals
               the old state, because the visibility <condition> already
               gates the button on `current.status == 'Open'`, and our
               only target newState is 'In Progress' so by definition we
               are changing state)
            3) Sets the new status (line 95: retval.setStatus(newState)) -
               mirrored here by `current.status = 'In Progress'`
            4) For "CLOSED" status, sets close timestamp (lines 97-100) -
               irrelevant for this UI Action which targets In Progress
            5) Saves the entity (line 102: getDao().save(retval)) -
               mirrored here by `current.update()`
            6) Raises an event for downstream listeners (line 106) -
               INTENTIONALLY OMITTED per the email-disabled constraint
               (AAP Section 0.7.2). ArkCase's raiseEvent() call would have
               triggered downstream notification listeners; the ServiceNow
               POC has no equivalent gs.eventQueue() call because email is
               disabled on the PDI and no other in-scope listeners need
               the event.

        That single Java method covered EVERY transition by string-matching
        the `newState` parameter. The ServiceNow target instead splits
        per-transition logic across:
          - This UI Action (Open -> In Progress, the start-progress edge)
          - Sibling UI Actions for every other transition
          - The central Script Include CaseTransitionValidator (single
            source of truth for transition guards, called from this UI
            Action AND from the Flow Designer subflow
            validate_inprogress_transition.xml AND from the validate_
            assigned_agent_membership Business Rule)
          - The two parent state-machine flows (which also trigger on
            this status change via their OnUpdate filters)
          - The validate_assigned_agent_membership business rule which
            runs on EVERY case update regardless of transition target,
            providing universal coverage even for direct Table API edits

    BUTTON VISIBILITY CONDITION (the <condition> field):

        The button is shown when ALL of the following are true:
          1) current.status == 'Open'   (the source state of the
             Open -> In Progress transition)
          2) The current user holds at least one of:
             - x_casemgmt_case_manager   (always permitted)
             - x_casemgmt_case_agent AND (current.assigned_agent ==
                gs.getUserID() OR current user is a member of
                current.assigned_group)
             (per AAP Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only" rule for case_agent)

        The visibility check runs server-side (the <condition> field is
        evaluated by the platform when rendering the form). The
        defense-in-depth check inside the <script> body re-validates the
        same conditions on the server when the button is clicked, providing
        two layers of validation that protect against:
          - Form-tampering attacks where the user edits hidden form fields
            to attempt the transition from a non-Open state
          - Race conditions where the user opens the form, the case
            transitions out of Open in another browser tab, then the
            user clicks Start Progress in the original tab
          - Role escalation attempts where a viewer somehow gains access
            to the form

    DELIBERATE OMISSION FROM VISIBILITY CONDITION (assigned_agent + membership
    check):

        The visibility <condition> deliberately does NOT include
        `current.assigned_agent != ''` or the membership check even though
        those are the actual preconditions checked by canTransitionToInProgress.
        This is intentional defense-in-depth UX:

          - If the button were hidden whenever assigned_agent is empty or
            the membership check fails, the user would have NO indication
            of how to advance the case. They would see an Open case with
            no transition button and be stuck guessing what to do.

          - With the button always visible on Open cases (subject only to
            the role+assignment gate), the user can click it and immediately
            receive the explicit blocking error "Assigned agent must be set
            and must be a member of the assigned group." (the verbatim error
            returned by canTransitionToInProgress). This tells them exactly
            what to do: populate assigned_agent with a member of
            assigned_group, then retry.

        This matches the AAP Section 0.5.5 row 2 "Surface form-level error"
        pattern - the user gets explicit feedback rather than a silently
        hidden control. The same UX philosophy applies to all sibling
        transition UI Actions in this folder (case_open.xml deliberately
        omits the assigned_group-populated check, case_resolve.xml will
        deliberately omit the all-tasks-closed check, etc.).

    DELEGATION TO SCRIPT INCLUDE (single source of truth):

        The transition-guard logic lives EXCLUSIVELY in
        ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml's
        canTransitionToInProgress(caseGr) method, which:

          - Takes the case GlideRecord as a parameter
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' }
            if caseGr is null/undefined
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'Assigned agent must be set and
            must be a member of the assigned group.' } if assigned_agent
            is null/empty/whitespace
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'Assigned agent must be set and
            must be a member of the assigned group.' } if assigned_group
            is null/empty/whitespace
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'Assigned agent must be set and
            must be a member of the assigned group.' } if isAgentInGroup
            (a GlideRecord lookup against sys_user_grmember) returns false
          - Returns { ok: true } if the transition is permitted

        The same helper is invoked by:
          - This UI Action (the form-button entry point)
          - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml (the Flow
            Designer subflow that fires on the OnUpdate trigger of the
            two parent state-machine flows)
          - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml
            (the before-update BR that runs on EVERY case update, catching
            non-form paths like Table API and scripted REST)
          - Any future scheduled job that performs Open -> In Progress
            transitions

        Centralizing the guard in the Script Include guarantees:
          - The error message text is identical across all callers
            (no drift between this UI Action, the flow subflow, and the BR)
          - Future rule changes (e.g., adding a third precondition like
            "assigned_agent must be active") only need to be made in
            one place
          - The single source of truth aligns with AAP Section 0.4.3
            "Shared transition-guard Script Include" design pattern

        The UI Action consumes the helper's { ok, error } contract:
            var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
            var result   = validator.canTransitionToInProgress(current);
            if (!result.ok) {
                gs.addErrorMessage(result.error);
                action.setRedirectURL(current);
                return;
            }
        It does NOT inline the assigned_agent + membership check. The
        Rule 5 in the AAP Section 0.7.2 ("Delegate to Script Include -
        DO NOT inline the membership check - Script Include is single
        source of truth") is honored.

    CHOICE-VALUE BYTE-FOR-BYTE REQUIREMENTS (AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim):

        The two case-status labels referenced in this UI Action are:

            'Open'         (4 chars, single word, Title Case)
            'In Progress'  (11 chars, two words, literal SPACE)

        These MUST match the labels in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
        byte-for-byte. ServiceNow Choice fields persist the LABEL string
        by default (not an integer ID), so the comparison is against the
        label text. Misspellings such as 'OPEN' (uppercase),
        'open' (lowercase), 'In_Progress' (underscore), 'InProgress'
        (no space), 'in progress' (lowercase), or 'IN PROGRESS'
        (uppercase) would silently never match and the UI Action would
        never fire.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table>x_casemgmt_case</table>             scoped table
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope>          scoped namespace
        - <sys_package>x_casemgmt</sys_package>      scoped application
        - <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
                                                     scoped roles
        - script body references current.status, current.assigned_agent,
          current.assigned_group (all on the scoped table x_casemgmt_case)
          and instantiates new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator() (the
          scoped Script Include)

        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables.
        Zero global ACL or role mutations.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table> resolves the case table BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <roles> resolves the two roles BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case_manager,
          x_casemgmt_case_agent)
        - The script body performs ZERO GlideRecord lookups by sys_id
          literal; it operates only on the platform-injected `current`
          GlideRecord and `gs.getUser()` / `gs.getUserID()` calls and
          delegates to the named Script Include via
          new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator(). The membership check
          inside the Script Include uses RUNTIME sys_id values read from
          the case record's assigned_agent and assigned_group fields,
          NOT hardcoded literals.
        - The script body uses NO gs.getReference() calls and NO
          GlideRecord.get(sys_id) calls.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_case_start_progress"), which is
          permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule applies
          to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to a
          record's own primary key.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This UI
        Action contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero gs.email() calls,
        and zero gs.notificationEngine() calls. It performs only the
        status update and an action.setRedirectURL refresh.

    NO PII CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body, code comments, description text, hint text, and
        all error messages contain zero real names, real email addresses,
        real phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any other
        personally identifiable information. The UI Action operates
        exclusively on synthetic case-status enumerations (Open,
        In Progress) and synthetic role identifiers (x_casemgmt_case_manager,
        x_casemgmt_case_agent).

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):

        This sys_ui_action record MUST be loaded AFTER:
            - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
              (the table this UI Action is bound to)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml
              (the field the visibility condition reads and the script writes)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent.xml
              (the field the visibility condition reads for the
               "Assigned only" check; the field the Script Include's
               canTransitionToInProgress validates is populated AND
               that the agent is a member of assigned_group)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group.xml
              (the field the visibility condition reads for the
               "Assigned only" check; the field the Script Include uses
               to verify the assigned_agent is a member)
            - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
              (the Open and In Progress Choice values)
            - ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
              (CRITICAL - the Script Include this UI Action delegates to;
               loading the UI Action before the Script Include would
               surface a runtime ReferenceError when the button is clicked
               and the platform attempts to instantiate
               x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator)
            - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml
              (the manager role referenced by <roles> and condition)
            - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_agent.xml
              (the agent role referenced by <roles> and condition)
            - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml
              (the scoped application)
            - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml
              (the scope record)

        And BEFORE:
            - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_02.xml
              (the Open-status demo case that exercises this UI Action;
               loading the demo case before this UI Action would still
               work since UI Actions are not invoked at load time, but
               the AAP-mandated load order keeps user-facing behavior
               artifacts ahead of demo data)
            - ../update-set/x_casemgmt_case_management_update_set.xml
              (the final aggregated Update Set that includes this record)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:

        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_case_start_progress")
               = e77dc24317a301765a60a3673ec7d164
        32-character lowercase hex. Recomputable via:
            printf '%s' 'x_casemgmt_case_start_progress' | md5sum | cut -c1-32

        Deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent re-import on a
        fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set produces the same
        sys_id, which collides on the existing record and updates it in
        place rather than creating a duplicate. This is the same convention
        used by the sibling Business Rules in
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_*.xml and the sibling UI Actions
        ../ui_action/x_casemgmt_case_open.xml,
        ../ui_action/x_casemgmt_case_resume.xml, and
        ../ui_action/x_casemgmt_case_set_pending.xml.

    ORDER WITHIN UI ACTION SEQUENCE:

        order=200 places Start Progress as the SECOND UI Action in the
        workflow sequence (between Open=100 and Set Pending=300):
            1) Open               (order=100       - Draft -> Open)
            2) Start Progress     (order=200, THIS  - Open -> In Progress)
            3) Set Pending        (order=300       - In Progress -> Pending)
            4) Resume             (order=400       - Pending -> In Progress)
            5) Resolve            (order=500       - In Progress -> Resolved)
            6) Close              (order=600, LAST  - Resolved -> Closed)

        The ordering is for UI display only - the platform renders form
        buttons in ascending order. Only one button is visible at a time
        (each visibility <condition> matches a different status), so the
        ordering does not affect runtime correctness. Start Progress
        carries order=200 because it is the second transition in the
        canonical forward sequence.

    FORM_STYLE = primary:

        Start Progress is the AFFIRMATIVE NEXT STEP from Open. The user
        wants to begin work on the case, so the button is rendered with
        the platform's primary visual style (typically a filled-color
        button) to draw attention. This contrasts with Set Pending,
        which uses form_style=secondary because pausing a case is a less
        common, less attention-grabbing action.

    MANAGER + ASSIGNED-AGENT VISIBILITY (AAP Section 0.5.6 verbatim):

        Both x_casemgmt_case_manager and assigned x_casemgmt_case_agent
        see the Start Progress button. case_viewer does NOT. The
        rationale per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix:

          - case_manager has full access ("Create=YES, Read=All, Write=All,
            Delete=YES") and can perform any transition on any case
            regardless of assignment.

          - case_agent has assigned-only access ("Create=YES, Read=Assigned
            only, Write=Assigned only, Delete=NO"). For the Start Progress
            transition, the agent must be either current.assigned_agent
            directly OR a member of current.assigned_group. This is
            enforced by:
              1) The visibility <condition> below (form-render time)
              2) The defense-in-depth re-check in the script body
                 (form-submit time)

          - case_viewer has read-only access ("Create=NO, Read=All,
            Write=NO, Delete=NO") and never gets transition buttons.
            case_viewer is excluded by the <roles> field below
            (comma-separated list contains case_manager and case_agent
            but NOT case_viewer).

        The two roles in <roles> below (x_casemgmt_case_manager,
        x_casemgmt_case_agent, comma-separated, no spaces) enforce this.
        The visibility <condition> further narrows case_agent visibility
        to "Assigned only" cases per AAP Section 0.5.6.

    DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH MEMBERSHIP CHECK (CRITICAL DESIGN DECISION):

        BOTH this UI Action's Script Include delegation AND
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml
        check that assigned_agent is a member of assigned_group on the
        Open -> In Progress transition. This is INTENTIONAL belt-and-
        suspenders defense in depth, NOT a bug or redundancy:

          * This UI Action's Script Include delegation (via
            canTransitionToInProgress) blocks the form-submit path before
            current.update() is called - the user gets immediate feedback
            on the form without a database round-trip for the failed
            update.

          * The companion BR's check ensures the membership invariant
            holds even if this transition is performed via:
              - The Table API (e.g., REST integration patching status)
              - A scripted REST endpoint that bypasses this UI Action
              - The Update Set seed data import path (if seed data ever
                violated the invariant, it would be caught at import time)
              - A scheduled job invoking GlideRecord.update()
              - Any other path that does not click the Start Progress button

          * Per AAP Section 0.7.2 "no out-of-scope workarounds when capability
            gaps are discovered": both layers are explicitly in scope as
            companion artifacts, not workarounds.

        The two checks happen in SEPARATE phases (this UI Action runs
        BEFORE current.update(); the BR runs DURING the before-update
        pipeline of that update). The UI Action provides BETTER UX (no
        wasted database write attempt), while the BR provides UNIVERSAL
        COVERAGE (catches non-form paths). They are complementary,
        not redundant.

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):

        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error". This
          UI Action implements the Open -> In Progress transition (per
          AAP Section 0.5.5 row 2). The Script Include's
          canTransitionToInProgress enforces "assigned_agent populated
          AND member of assigned_group" and surfaces a blocking
          gs.addErrorMessage if violated. The defense-in-depth role,
          status, and "Assigned only" re-checks prevent stale-form
          submissions from corrupting the state machine.

        - Gate 3 (ACLs): "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot
          write; case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager
          has full access". This UI Action's visibility <condition> and
          server-side defense-in-depth check both encode the role rules
          from AAP Section 0.5.6 verbatim. case_viewer is excluded by the
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
          field. case_agent on an unassigned case is excluded by the
          "Assigned only" sub-condition.

        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set loads
          without errors on a fresh PDI instance". The deterministic
          sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and absence of any external
          lookups guarantee this UI Action re-imports cleanly with zero
          preview errors.

    COMPANION ARTIFACTS:

        This UI Action handles the Open -> In Progress transition at the
        FORM-LEVEL (button click). Companion artifacts:

          - ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
            (the central transition-guard helper; this UI Action's
             canTransitionToInProgress call delegates to its method of
             the same name)
          - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml
            (the Flow Designer subflow that runs the SAME guard via
             the parent state-machine flows' OnUpdate trigger; covers
             non-form transition paths like Table API and scripted REST)
          - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml
            (the before-update BR that runs the SAME membership check on
             EVERY case update; ensures the invariant holds regardless
             of which interface initiates the transition)
          - ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
            (the housekeeping BR that clears pending_reason on transitions
             INTO In Progress; for the Open -> In Progress edge there is
             typically no pending_reason set anyway, but the BR is a
             no-op in that case)
          - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (parent OnUpdate flow filtered on type=General Inquiry; fires
             on this transition and re-validates via the
             validate_inprogress_transition subflow)
          - ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml
            (parent OnUpdate flow filtered on type=Complaint; fires on
             this transition and re-validates via the
             validate_inprogress_transition subflow)

        The UI Action provides the FORM-LEVEL entry point (button). The
        Script Include provides the GUARD LOGIC (single source of truth).
        The flows provide the WORKFLOW-LEVEL hook (covers non-form paths).
        The business rules provide the FIELD-LEVEL housekeeping
        (clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress) and the UNIVERSAL membership
        check (validate_assigned_agent_membership). They are
        complementary, not redundant.

